      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome, and thanks for joining this course on AI and regulatory compliance in financial services. If you're working in this sector, you'll already know that AI is changing things fast. Firms are using it to make lending decisions, flag suspicious transactions, assess risk, and personalise services for customers. But here's the thing: when a machine is making decisions that affect someone's mortgage application or their credit score, the stakes are genuinely high. That's exactly why regulators are watching this space so closely. The greater the potential impact on people's financial lives, the greater the expectation that firms can explain, justify, and stand behind those decisions. This course is here to help you make sense of that landscape. By the end, you'll have a clearer picture of what the rules require, why they exist, and how you can work with AI tools in a way that's both responsible and confident. Let's get started."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "So let us be very clear about where we are right now. Regulators around the world are paying extremely close attention to how organisations are using artificial intelligence. This is not something that is coming in the future. It is happening today. The rules and expectations around AI are evolving quickly, and they are becoming more demanding, not less. And it is important to understand that no sector is exempt from this. Whether you are in banking, insurance, investment management, or any other part of financial services, scrutiny is coming your way. The consequences of getting this wrong are serious. We are talking about financial penalties, reputational damage, and in some cases, restrictions on how you can operate. Regulators are not simply observing and waiting. They expect firms to be taking action now, building the right frameworks, asking the right questions, and demonstrating that AI is being used responsibly. That is the environment we are all operating in."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So here is something that has really shifted in recent years. Regulators are no longer just setting rules and hoping firms follow them. They are actively looking under the bonnet at how AI systems are making decisions, and if they find something they do not like, the financial penalties can be significant and are only going up. One of the biggest changes is around explainability. You cannot simply say \"the algorithm decided it.\" You need to be able to explain why a decision was made, in plain terms. Alongside that, having a human in the loop is no longer optional. There must be genuine human oversight of AI-driven processes. And all of this needs to be documented properly. Regulators want a clear paper trail showing what your AI is doing, how it is being monitored, and who is responsible. So if your organisation is using AI in any part of its compliance or decision-making processes, now is absolutely the time to get your house in order."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "So why are regulators paying such close attention to AI right now? Well, the core issue is that AI systems can make thousands of decisions in the time it takes a human to review just one. That speed and scale makes oversight genuinely difficult. Regulators are particularly concerned about three things: bias creeping into decisions, a lack of transparency about how those decisions are being made, and uncertainty about who is actually responsible when something goes wrong. Financial services is already one of the most heavily regulated sectors out there, and AI raises the stakes considerably. If a flawed model is making lending or fraud decisions, it could affect huge numbers of customers before anyone even spots the problem. And when things do go wrong, if there is no clear owner of that AI system, accountability becomes very murky very quickly. That combination of speed, opacity, and unclear responsibility is exactly what keeps regulators up at night."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So what does regulatory scrutiny actually look like when it comes to AI? Well, regulators do not simply trust that your AI system is working correctly. They will actively examine it. They want to understand how decisions are being made, and crucially, they expect you to be able to explain those decisions in plain terms. If your model is a so-called black box, where even you cannot explain why it reached a particular outcome, that is going to raise serious concerns. Regulators see that as a risk, and rightly so. They will also want to see proper audit trails, meaning detailed logs that show what the system did, when it did it, and why. And bias is a major focus too. You will be expected to demonstrate that your AI is not systematically disadvantaging any particular group of customers. In short, regulators want transparency, accountability, and evidence. Not just good intentions."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So, how do regulators actually expect firms to behave when they're using AI? Well, the short answer is: with transparency and clear accountability. Supervisory bodies want to see that you can explain how your AI systems reach their conclusions. If you can't explain a decision, that's a serious problem. You also need to be regularly testing and validating your models, not just when you first deploy them, but on an ongoing basis, to show that they're still performing as expected. Keeping detailed audit trails of what your AI has produced is equally important, because if a regulator comes knocking, you'll want that evidence ready. And perhaps most critically, someone in your organisation needs to be clearly responsible for the decisions that AI is driving. Regulators are not comfortable with the idea that \"the algorithm decided.\" There must always be a human being who owns that outcome and can be held to account."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So, how do you actually prepare for the moment a regulator comes asking questions? The honest answer is that you cannot leave it until that moment arrives. You need to be ready well in advance. That means documenting how your AI systems reach their decisions, keeping a clear log of any updates or changes to your models, and making sure someone specific is named as responsible for each tool you are using. It also means running your own internal audits regularly, so you are not caught off guard. Crucially, you should be able to point to each AI application and say exactly which regulatory rule it relates to. And all of that documentation needs to be well organised and easy to retrieve at short notice, not buried in a shared drive somewhere. Regulators want to see that you are in control of your AI, and good record keeping is how you demonstrate that."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring everything together from this lesson. The core message is this: AI is under the microscope from regulators, and that scrutiny is only going to increase. When you deploy AI in a financial services context, you need to be able to explain how it reaches its conclusions, because \"the algorithm decided\" simply is not good enough. You also need to be actively watching for bias in your models, because unfair outcomes can cause real harm to customers and serious reputational damage to your firm. Every decision your AI makes should be documented, so that you have a clear audit trail if questions are ever raised. Regulators are also very clear that a human being must remain in the loop, responsible and accountable. And finally, do not wait for a regulatory review to prompt you into action. Take a look at your AI policies right now, and make sure they are fit for purpose."
        }
      ]
